        I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<span class="line"><!---->I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<!----></span><br><br>What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <span class="line"><!---->What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <!----></span>comment 2<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c2"><!---->comment 2<!----></a> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <span class="line"><!----> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<!----></a>,<span class="line"><!---->,<!----></span> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<span class="line"><!----> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<!----></span><br><br>I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<span class="line"><!---->I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        VULNERABILITY DETAILS<b class="line"><!---->VULNERABILITY DETAILS<!----></b><br>Reloading an extension while the service worker is paused on a debugger breakpoint in the `chrome.runtime.onInstalled` callback causes heap-UAF.<span class="line"><!---->Reloading an extension while the service worker is paused on a debugger breakpoint in the `chrome.runtime.onInstalled` callback causes heap-UAF.<!----></span><br><br>STEPS TO REPRODUCE<b class="line"><!---->STEPS TO REPRODUCE<!----></b><br>1. Install the attached extension (no permissions)<span class="line"><!---->1. Install the attached extension (no permissions)<!----></span><br>2. Click on Inspect service worker<span class="line"><!---->2. Click on Inspect service worker<!----></span><br>3. Reload the extension (by clicking the reload button or with `chrome.runtime.reload()`)<span class="line"><!---->3. Reload the extension (by clicking the reload button or with `chrome.runtime.reload()`)<!----></span><br><br><br>Tested in <span class="line"><!---->Tested in <!----></span>r1114555<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://crrev.com/1114555"><!---->r1114555<!----></a>, see <span class="line"><!---->, see <!----></span>#c3<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c3"><!---->#c3<!----></a> for affected versions. Does not repro on <span class="line"><!----> for affected versions.         I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<span class="line"><!---->I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<!----></span><br><br>What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <span class="line"><!---->What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <!----></span>comment 2<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c2"><!---->comment 2<!----></a> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <span class="line"><!----> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<!----></a>,<span class="line"><!---->,<!----></span> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<span class="line"><!----> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<!----></span><br><br>I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<span class="line"><!---->I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

          Comment 8<a class="comment-link" href="?id=1423656#c8">Comment 8<!----></a>

          
        by
        
      <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/icon?family=Material+Icons" rel="stylesheet">
      schedule<i id="availability-icon" class="material-icons inline-icon ${user.last_visit_timestamp ? '': 'inline-icon-unseen'}" title="undefined" hidden="">schedule</i>
      pkasting@chromium.org<a id="user-link" href="/u/2899342933" title="pkasting@chromium.org"><!---->pkasting@chromium.org<!----></a>
      pkasting@chromium.org<span id="user-text" hidden=""><!---->pkasting@chromium.org<!----></span>
      <div id="availability-text" class="availability-notice" title="undefined" hidden=""><!----><!----></div>
    <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>
        on
        
      Mon, Mar 13, 2023, 7:31 PM EDT
    <chops-timestamp title="Mon, Mar 13, 2023, 7:31 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
          Project Member<span class="role-label">Project Member</span>
      
        <div>
          <a class="comment-link" href="?id=1423656#c8">Comment 8<!----></a>

          
        by
        <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>
        on
        <chops-timestamp title="Mon, Mar 13, 2023, 7:31 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
          <span class="role-label">Project Member</span>
      
        </div>
        
      <div role="heading" class="comment-header" aria-level="2">
        <div>
          <a class="comment-link" href="?id=1423656#c8">Comment 8<!----></a>

          
        by
        <mr-user-link></mr-user-link>
        on
        <chops-timestamp title="Mon, Mar 13, 2023, 7:31 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
          <span class="role-label">Project Member</span>
      
        </div>
        
      </div>
    
      
        
      
        
          Owner:<strong><!---->Owner:</strong>
          
          lazyboy@chromium.org
          
          <br>
        
        
      <div class="issue-diff">
        <!---->
          <strong><!---->Owner:</strong>
          
          lazyboy@chromium.org
          
          <br>
        <!---->
        
      </div><br>
    
        
      
        I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<span class="line"><!---->I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<!----></span><br><br>What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <span class="line"><!---->What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <!----></span>comment 2<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c2"><!---->comment 2<!----></a> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <span class="line"><!----> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<!----></a>,<span class="line"><!---->,<!----></span> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<span class="line"><!----> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<!----></span><br><br>I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<span class="line"><!---->I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>
        
          
        <div>
          
        </div>
      <div class="comment-body">

        <chops-timestamp title="Mon, Mar 13, 2023, 4:13 PM EDT"></chops-timestamp>
        
      
        </div>
        
      </div>
    
      
        
        
      
        VULNERABILITY DETAILS<b class="line"><!---->VULNERABILITY DETAILS<!----></b><br>Reloading an extension while the service worker is paused on a debugger breakpoint in the `chrome.runtime.onInstalled` callback causes heap-UAF.<span class="line"><!---->Reloading an extension while the service worker is paused on a debugger breakpoint in the `chrome.runtime.onInstalled` callback causes heap-UAF.<!----></span><br><br>STEPS TO REPRODUCE<b class="line"><!---->STEPS TO REPRODUCE<!----></b><br>1. Install the attached extension (no permissions)<span class="line"><!---->1. Install the attached extension (no permissions)<!----></span><br>2. Click on Inspect service worker<span class="line"><!---->2. Click on Inspect service worker<!----></span><br>3. Reload the extension (by clicking the reload button or with `chrome.runtime.reload()`)<span class="line"><!---->3. Reload the extension (by clicking the reload button or with `chrome.runtime.reload()`)<!----></span><br><br><br>Tested in <span class="line"><!---->Tested in <!----></span>r1114555<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://crrev.com/1114555"><!---->r1114555<!----></a>, see <span class="line"><!---->, see <!----></span>#c3<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c3"><!---->#c3<!----></a> for affected versions. Does not repro on <span class="line"><!----> for affected versions. Does not repro on <!----></span>r1114579<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://crrev.com/1114579"><!---->r1114579<!----></a> and newer.<span class="line"><!----> and newer.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<span class="line"><!---->I suspect that my CL changes this from a UAF to a null deref. If that's preferable you can try to merge back, although I'd be a little leery of doing so, since `thread_local` seems to be filled with dragons.<!----></span><br><br>What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <span class="line"><!---->What I believe is happening from reading the stacks in <!----></span>comment 2<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="#c2"><!---->comment 2<!----></a> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <span class="line"><!----> -- although it isn't 100% clear to me -- is that something, perhaps <!----></span>https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<a class="undefined" target="_blank" href="https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55"><!---->https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:extensions/renderer/worker_thread_dispatcher.cc;l=392;drc=1cb13ea510f483d4c8e48b9239c446b67316ca55<!----></a>,<span class="line"><!---->,<!----></span> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<span class="line"><!----> is resulting in spinning a nested message loop between the null-check of the thread-local pointer atop WorkerThreadDispatcher::DispatchEventHelper() and the use of that pointer at the end of that function. This nested message loop is freeing the pointer and resetting the thread-local object to point to null. The difference before and after my patch is that before my patch we have a ThreadLocalPointer object and afterward we have a direct thread_local. So beforehand, the underlying pointer is freed and then `g_data_tls` is set to null, but anyone still holding `g_data_tls.Get()` (as this function is) will be holding a dangling pointer. Afterward, we're using the thread_local pointer directly, so when we return from the nested message loop, the thing we're dereffing is null. (Which will presumably crash.)<!----></span><br><br>I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<span class="line"><!---->I don't know this code's invariants, so I don't know if the fix is to not spin a nested loop, or to save off the necessary state before possibly spinning it, or to null-check-and-bail on return from it. Sending to lazyboy@ based on blame.<!----></span><mr-comment-content></mr-comment-content>

        /*
         * Really specific class names are necessary because ShadowDOM
         * is disabled for this component.
         */
        .chops-autocomplete-container {
          position: relative;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container table {
          padding: 0;
          font-size: var(--chops-main-font-size);
          color: var(--chops-link-color);
          position: absolute;
          background: var(--chops-white);
          border: var(--chops-accessible-border);
          z-index: 999;
          box-shadow: 2px 3px 8px 0px hsla(0, 0%, 0%, 0.3);
          border-spacing: 0;
          border-collapse: collapse;
          /* In the case when the autocomplete extends the
           * height of the viewport, we want to make sure
           * there's spacing. */
          margin-bottom: 1em;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tbody {
          display: block;
          min-width: 100px;
          max-height: 500px;
          overflow: auto;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tr {
          cursor: pointer;
          transition: background 0.2s ease-in-out;
        }
        .chops-autocomplete-container tr[data-selected] {
          background: var(--chops-active-choice-bg);
          text-decoration: underline;

 runOnLoad(function() {
 if (typeof(ClientLogger) === "function") {
 let cl = new ClientLogger("issues");
 if (cl.started("new-issue")) {
 cl.logEnd("new-issue", null, 120 * 1000);
 }
 if (cl.started("issue-search")) {
 cl.logEnd("issue-search");
 }
 }
 });
